# Aura Presentation Mentor: Architecture & Implementation Plan

## 1) One-paragraph product spec:
The **Aura Presentation Mentor** is a real-time, multi-modal Live Agent designed for professionals and students to practice high-stakes presentations (pitches, interviews, keynotes). The core loop involves the user presenting naturally to their webcam and microphone while the agent acts as an active, empathic audience—reacting, interrupting with realistic questions, and providing live, non-distracting visual cues. Unlike simple post-hoc analysis tools, Aura is truly *agentic*: it dynamically adapts its persona (friendly coach vs. aggressive VC), actively probes weak points in the user's rhetoric via barge-in, and orchestrates specialized sub-agents to deliver holistic, contextual feedback on delivery, content, and body language in real time.

## 2) SOTA Techniques We'll Use:
* **Streaming Multimodal Understanding:** Ingesting WebRTC audio and video frames continuously into Gemini Live for zero-shot behavioral analysis without intermediate transcription delays.
* **Interruption Handling ("Barge-in"):** Utilizing the Gemini Live API's native full-duplex capabilities to allow the user to interrupt the agent's feedback, and allowing the agent to interrupt the user to simulate tough Q&A.
* **Multi-Agent Evaluation:** A MoE (Mixture of Experts) inspired orchestration layer where distinct sub-agents evaluate non-overlapping rubrics (Delivery, Content, Body Language) simultaneously.
* **Rubric-Based Scoring:** Structured JSON output from agents evaluating specific metrics (e.g., filler word frequency, eye contact percentage, rhetorical strength).
* **Temporal Smoothing:** Using moving averages and hysteresis on visual feedback UI to prevent flickering alerts (e.g., only show "speak louder" if volume is consistently low for >2 seconds).
* **Calibration & Personalization:** A 30-second baseline calibration at the start to adjust thresholds for the user's natural speaking rate, accent, and baseline posture.
* **Safety & Guardrails:** Real-time toxicity filtering and failure-mode recovery (e.g., gracefully handling sudden camera occlusion or unintelligible audio).
* **Novelty 1 - Adversarial Audience Simulation (Shark Mode):** The agent dynamically changes tone and interrupts the user with challenging, context-aware questions mid-pitch to test composure under pressure.
* **Novelty 2 - Live Re-takes & Context Memory:** The user can say "Let me try that slide again," and the agent instantly marks the timeline, forgets the bad take's penalty, and compares the new delivery against the previous one using session memory.
* **Novelty 3 - Style Transfer for Feedback Tone:** The Meta-Orchestrator dynamically alters the TTS output tone to match the selected persona (e.g., supportive mentor vs. strict evaluator).

## 3) Multi-agent design:
* **Meta-Orchestrator Agent:**
  * *Inputs:* User audio/video stream, outputs from all sub-agents.
  * *Outputs:* Final voice responses, UI control signals.
  * *Rubric/Role:* Manages conversation state, handles persona switching, decides *when* to interrupt.
  * *Conflict Resolution:* If Delivery Coach says "interrupt for pacing" but Content Coach says "they are making a crucial point," Orchestrator prioritizes Content and delays the pacing feedback to the post-pitch summary.
* **Delivery & Vocal Coach Agent:**
  * *Inputs:* Audio stream (features: pitch, volume, pacing, filler words).
  * *Outputs:* Real-time pacing/volume flags, post-pitch vocal scorecard.
  * *Rubric:* WPM (120-160 ideal), pauses > 2s, filler word count ("um", "uh"), intonation variance.
* **Body Language & Vision Agent:**
  * *Inputs:* Video frame samples (1 fps).
  * *Outputs:* Posture alerts, eye-contact metrics, hand-gesture analysis.
  * *Rubric:* Eye contact with lens (>70%), slouching detection, nervous repetitive movements.
* **Content & Rhetoric Coach Agent:**
  * *Inputs:* Streaming audio transcript/semantic meaning.
  * *Outputs:* Logic flow analysis, persuasion strength, identifying missing key points.
  * *Rubric:* Clarity of value proposition, logical transitions, handling of Q&A.
* **Audience Q&A Simulation Agent (Adversary):**
  * *Inputs:* Content Coach outputs, user audio.
  * *Outputs:* Generated challenging questions contextually relevant to the current topic.
  * *Rubric:* Relevance of question to the immediate context, conversational naturalness.

## 4) Google Cloud architecture:
*   **Web Client:** Next.js React frontend (Vercel or Cloud Run).
*   **Real-time Layer:** WebSockets.
*   **Backend:** Node.js (TypeScript) on **Google Cloud Run** for scalable connection handling.
*   **AI Engine:** **Vertex AI with Gemini Live API** for multimodal streaming (audio + video frames) and high-speed bidirectional voice.
*   **Storage:** **Cloud SQL** (PostgreSQL) for user profiles and session metadata. **Cloud Storage** for optional post-session video highlights/reports.
*   **Monitoring:** **Cloud Logging & Monitoring** to track latency and API quotas.

```mermaid
graph TD
    Client[Next.js Client] <-->|WebSockets: Audio+Video+JSON| CR[Cloud Run Backend Node.js]
    CR <-->|Vertex AI Gemini Live API| GeminiLive[Gemini Live]
    CR -->|Store Session Metadata| SQL[Cloud SQL]
    CR -->|Store Highlights| GCS[Cloud Storage]
    CR -->|Emit Logs & Metrics| Logs[Cloud Logging]

    subgraph "Agentic Logic (Within Cloud Run / Gemini System)"
        Orchestrator[Meta-Orchestrator]
        Delivery[Delivery Coach]
        Vision[Body Language Coach]
        Content[Content Coach]
        Adversary[Adversary Q&A Agent]
        
        GeminiLive -.-> Orchestrator
        Orchestrator -.-> Delivery
        Orchestrator -.-> Vision
        Orchestrator -.-> Content
        Orchestrator -.-> Adversary
    end
```

## 5) Data flow & real-time loop:
1. **Ingestion:** Client captures mic (PCM 16kHz) and webcam frames (downscaled JPEG at 1 fps). Sends to Node.js backend via WebSockets.
2. **Forwarding:** Node.js backend maintains a bidirectional gRPC/WebSocket connection to Vertex AI Gemini Live API, streaming the multimodal data.
3. **Sub-Agent Processing:** As the user speaks, background context prompts instruct Gemini to extract metrics (Content, Delivery, Vision) and generate structured JSON scorecards continuously alongside semantic understanding.
4. **Evaluation:** The Meta-Orchestrator evaluates this JSON. If a critical threshold is met (e.g., user is completely off-script), it triggers an intervention.
5. **Feedback Generation:** The Orchestrator streams an audio response back through Gemini Live to the backend.
6. **UI Update:** Backend sends the audio buffer + UI control JSON (e.g., `{"alert": "eye_contact_low"}`) to the client.
7. **Barge-in / Interruption:** If the agent is talking and the user interrupts, the client's Voice Activity Detection (VAD) instantly sends a `cancel_playback` flag to the backend. The backend stops sending the agent's audio to the client and signals the Gemini Live API that the turn is complete, avoiding "talking over" the user.

## 6) Multimodal outputs:
1. **Real-time Visual Cues (Overlay):** Minimalist UI indicators driven by JSON data streams. For example, a subtle pulsing border turns orange if the user is speaking too fast, and a posture icon flashes gently if they begin to slouch.
2. **Structured Scorecards + Timeline Graphs:** A detailed post-presentation dashboard using Recharts. It maps pacing, volume, and eye contact over a temporal graph, correlated exactly with the presentation transcript to identify weak moments.
3. **Generated Highlight Reel:** If the user enables recording, the backend marks timestamps of "best areas" and "needs improvement". Post-session, FFMPEG on Cloud Run generates short 10-second clips with burned-in feedback overlays (e.g., a green checkmark when a strong value proposition is uttered).

## 7) MVP Plan (build order):
1. [ ] **Repo & GCP Setup:** Init Next.js + Node.js backend. Deploy skeleton to Cloud Run. Setup Vertex AI credentials.
2. [ ] **Audio Streaming Plumbing:** Implement WebRTC/WebSocket to stream raw audio from browser to Node.js and back.
3. [ ] **Gemini Live API Integration:** Connect Node.js to Vertex AI Gemini Live API. Establish low-latency conversational audio.
4. [ ] **Video Frame Extraction:** Add 1fps JPEG capture from webcam -> WebSocket -> Gemini Live API.
5. [ ] **VAD & Barge-in:** Implement Voice Activity Detection on the client to handle interruptions.
6. [ ] **Structured Extraction:** Engineer prompts to output JSON metrics (pacing, eye contact) alongside conversation.
7. [ ] **Real-time UI Overlays:** Wire the JSON metrics to visual cues in the Next.js React frontend.
8. [ ] **Post-Session Dashboard:** Build the timeline graph and scorecard UI using aggregated session data.
9. [ ] **Polish & Deploy:** Finalize Cloud Run deployment and setup Cloud Logging.
10. [ ] **Record Demo Video:** Run the proof loops.

## 8) Proof-of-GCP plan:
* **Screen Recording Plan:** We will record a 2-minute video showing the live Next.js app functioning (Agent responding to voice + video). Midway through, we will visibly switch to the **Google Cloud Console**, navigate to **Cloud Logging**, and filter for `logName="projects/[PROJECT_ID]/logs/run.googleapis.com%2Fstdout"`. We will show real-time JSON log entries of the WebSocket payloads and Gemini Live latency metrics pouring in as the user speaks.
* **Code Repo Proof:** In the GitHub repo, we will include a file named `src/services/gemini-live-client.ts` that explicitly imports `@google-cloud/vertexai` and manages the connection to the Vertex AI endpoints. We will link this specifically in our `README.md` as our proof of implementation.

## 9) Risks & mitigations:
* **Latency:** *Risk:* High latency ruins the "Live" feel. *Mitigation:* Use WebSockets instead of HTTP polling. Keep video frame rate low (1 fps, strong compression). Process audio in discrete chunks.
* **Interruption Handling (Talking over):** *Risk:* Agent keeps talking while user speaks. *Mitigation:* Strict client-side VAD to instantly mute the agent's playback the millisecond user speech is registered, combined with server-side cancellation.
* **Cost/Quotas:** *Risk:* Streaming multi-modal to Gemini is computationally expensive. *Mitigation:* Aggressive downsampling of video frames (e.g., 512x512 max). Stop sending video frames if no motion is detected. Use a smaller model tier (like Gemini 1.5 Flash) optimized for speed.
* **Privacy:** *Risk:* Users are hesitant to stream video. *Mitigation:* Clear consent UI. No raw video is saved to Cloud Storage unless the user explicitly toggles "Save Session for Review". Video chunks are kept only in memory in Cloud Run and discarded immediately.
* **Hallucinations in Feedback:** *Risk:* Agent gives mathematically wrong pacing stats. *Mitigation:* Rely on deterministic code (e.g., client-side word frequency counters) for hard metrics like WPM, and restrict the LLM primarily to qualitative rhetorical feedback.
